A hands-on follow-up to Understanding LLM Streaming: Polling, SSE, and WebSockets. Part 1 explained the ideas. This one is me putting them to the test, and being a little surprised.
Part 1 walked through the three ways to stream tokens from an LLM (polling, SSE, and WebSockets), and why SSE tends to be the natural fit for one-way text generation. What it didn’t have was a single number. It was all concepts and diagrams; I never put a stopwatch on any of it.
This time I did. I built all three transports (polling, SSE, WebSockets), fed them the exact same token stream, and measured everything: first-token time, total time, request count, bytes, even server CPU and memory. Polling shows up in two forms, short and long, and I built both, so there were really four horses in this race. A tiny FastAPI backend, one HTML file, no React, no Docker. First with one user, then, because I got curious, with ten thousand.
A couple of the results caught me off guard.

The setup
Everything runs against the same fake “model”: a fixed 10-token stream where each token takes 300 ms to generate, simulated with an asyncio.sleep, not a real GPU. That’s the whole point: this benchmark measures transport, not inference. Every protocol is handed the exact same token schedule, so nothing here is a claim about how fast a model runs, only about the pipe you run it through.
The reason that 300 ms matters so much comes down to how a real model works. It writes its answer one token at a time, in order. Token #5 simply doesn’t exist yet while the model is still busy on token #3. Ask for it early and there’s nothing to hand back; it hasn’t been written. This benchmark enforces exactly that: if a token hasn’t been generated yet, nobody gets it, no matter which transport is asking. That one rule is what makes the comparison meaningful.
TOKENS = ["Hello", "world", ",", "this", "is", "a", "streamed", "LLM", "response", "."]
DELAY_MS = 0.3 # simulate 300 ms of "thinking" per tokenThe demo puts four panels side by side, all streaming the same sentence, with a live metrics table running underneath, so every contender races in one view.
A fair fight. For the comparison to mean anything, the only thing that changes between the runs is the transport. Everything else is held identical: the same token generator, the same 300 ms delay, the same FastAPI backend, the same machine, the same browser, the same JSON serialization, the same payload. Nobody gets a head start, and nothing is measuring the “model.”
Test environment. For the numbers to be reproducible: one uvicorn worker (single process, no --workers), FastAPI 0.104 / Starlette 0.27 on Python 3.11, Windows 10, a 6-core / 12-thread CPU with 16 GB RAM. The load generator is thread-per-client running on the same box. Deliberately modest: the point isn’t the absolute milliseconds, it’s the ratios between transports, and those hold whatever hardware you run this on.
