Short poll, long poll, SSE and WebSocket, all streaming the same sentence side by sideNow to build them.

Polling
Polling is beautifully dumb, and I mean that with affection. The client just keeps knocking on the door: got the next token yet? … how about now? … now?
Part 1 split polling in two. Short polling asks again on a fixed timer. Long polling makes the server hold each request open until it has a token to hand back. I built both, and they behave differently enough that they earn separate rows in every table below. Short polling first, since it’s the simpler of the two.
The tricky part was making it fair. The token you ask for should only become available once it’s been “generated.” So the server withholds it: the client sends back a start time t0, and the server checks whether the token you’re asking for has been produced yet.
@app.get("/poll")
def poll(index: int = 0, t0: float = 0.0):
now = time.time()
if not t0:
t0 = now # first knock starts the clock if index >= len(TOKENS):
return {"done": True, "ready": True, "t0": t0} # token `index` doesn't exist until t0 + (index + 1) * 300ms
if now < t0 + (index + 1) * DELAY_MS:
return {"token": None, "ready": False, "t0": t0} # nothing yet, a wasted poll return {"token": TOKENS[index], "ready": True, "index": index + 1, "t0": t0}And the client just won’t stop asking:
let index = 0, t0 = 0;
const poll = async () => {
const { token, ready, index: next, done, t0: start } = await (
await fetch(`/poll?index=${index}&t0=${t0}`)
).json();
t0 = start;
if (ready && token) { appendToken(token); index = next; }
if (!done) setTimeout(poll, 300);
};The moment you open the Network tab, one thing jumps out: a dozen poll?index=N rows for a ten-word sentence. Those twelve break down like this: ten of them each land a token; one arrives a hair early and comes back empty (the token just wasn’t ready yet); and a final request asks for token #11 and gets done. Ten useful, two pure overhead. Those empties even have a name: wasted polls. A full round trip, and the server had nothing to give you.
Long polling: smarter, but not a cure
Part 1 called long polling “smarter than short polling,” and it is. The client stops knocking on a timer. Instead the server holds the request open until the token is actually ready, then answers, and the client asks again the moment it gets a reply.
@app.get("/longpoll")
async def longpoll(request: Request, index: int = 0, t0: float = 0.0):
ready_at = t0 + (index + 1) * DELAY_MS # when this token finishes generating
while time.time() < ready_at: # hold the request open until it exists
if await request.is_disconnected():
return {"token": None, "ready": False} # client left -> stop waiting
await asyncio.sleep(ready_at - time.time())
return {"token": TOKENS[index], "ready": True, "index": index + 1, "t0": t0}The client loop is the short-polling loop with the timer deleted:
const longpoll = async () => {
const { token, index: next, done } = await (
await fetch(`/longpoll?index=${index}&t0=${t0}`)
).json();
if (token) { appendToken(token); index = next; }
if (!done) longpoll(); // no setTimeout: the server already did the waiting
};Two things change immediately. The empty responses vanish, because the server never says “not ready,” it just waits. And first-token latency drops to the generation cadence with no interval to tune. On one user, long polling ties SSE and WebSocket on latency and total time, with zero wasted polls.
But look at what doesn’t change: it’s still one HTTP request per token. Short polling fired a dozen; long polling fires eleven. Both are a world away from SSE and WebSocket’s single connection. Long polling fixes short polling’s two ugliest symptoms, latency and waste, and leaves the underlying condition untouched: the request count still grows with tokens, not with one stream. Hold that thought for the scaling test, where it turns into the whole story.

SSE
Server-Sent Events sounds fancier than it is. It’s just one HTTP response that the server keeps writing to instead of closing. That’s the whole idea, and it’s also what OpenAI, Anthropic, and Cohere stream over. You’ve been on the receiving end of SSE every time you watched ChatGPT type.
async def sse_generator(request: Request, start: int = 0):
yield "retry: 3000\n\n" # how long to wait before reconnecting
for i in range(start, len(TOKENS)):
await asyncio.sleep(DELAY_MS) # simulate generating this token
if await request.is_disconnected():
return # nobody's home -> stop
yield f"id: {i}\n"
yield f"data: {json.dumps({'token': TOKENS[i], 'index': i + 1})}\n\n"And the client is almost embarrassingly small:
const es = new EventSource('/sse');
es.onmessage = (e) => {
const { token } = JSON.parse(e.data);
if (token) appendToken(token);
};Two little lines in there are the difference between a demo and something you’d actually ship.
That id: on every event lets the stream resume itself. When the connection drops on flaky train Wi-Fi, the browser reconnects, tells the server the last id it saw, and picks up where it left off. You wrote zero code for that.
And request.is_disconnected() means the server stops generating the moment you close the tab. On a real model, that’s GPU money you just stopped burning on someone who already left.
One production gotcha worth knowing. A yield doesn’t guarantee the byte actually leaves the building. Put an nginx (or most reverse proxies) in front, and it may happily buffer your whole response and deliver it in one lump, turning a smooth token trickle into a single late splat. The fix is telling the proxy to stop: the endpoint above already sends X-Accel-Buffering: no, and on the nginx side you’d set proxy_buffering off. If your streaming “works locally but batches in production,” this is almost always why.
There’s also a quieter ceiling: under HTTP/1.1 a browser allows only ~6 concurrent connections per origin, and an open EventSource holds one of those for its entire life. That’s a non-issue for an LLM chat (one stream per tab), but fan out a dozen SSE streams to the same host and the seventh just sits there waiting. HTTP/2 (connection multiplexing) makes the limit disappear.
In the Network tab, this whole thing is one row. Type: eventsource. One connection, tokens trickling down it. Compare that to the dozen rows polling left behind.

WebSockets
For plain token streaming, WebSockets are overkill. But they can do one thing SSE can’t: let the client interrupt mid-stream.
Think about the Stop button in every serious chat UI. You hit it halfway through a rambling answer and generation stops. That button only works because of a WebSocket. SSE can’t do it, because SSE only knows how to talk in one direction.
@app.websocket("/ws")
async def websocket_endpoint(websocket: WebSocket):
await websocket.accept()
cancelled = asyncio.Event() async def listen_for_cancel():
while not cancelled.is_set():
msg = await websocket.receive_text()
if "cancel" in msg.lower() or "stop" in msg.lower():
cancelled.set(); return
listener = asyncio.create_task(listen_for_cancel())
try:
for i, token in enumerate(TOKENS):
await asyncio.sleep(DELAY_MS)
if cancelled.is_set():
await websocket.send_json({"cancelled": True}); break
await websocket.send_json({"token": token, "index": i + 1})
finally:
cancelled.set(); listener.cancel() # skip this and you leak a task per connection
const ws = new WebSocket(`ws://${location.host}/ws`);
ws.onmessage = (e) => {
const { token } = JSON.parse(e.data);
if (token) appendToken(token);
};
stopBtn.onclick = () => ws.send('cancel'); // the move SSE can't makeBut there’s a bill, and it comes due in complexity. Now you own reconnection. You own the connection lifecycle. You own that cleanup in the finally: forget it, and you’re leaking a background task on every connection until your server falls over. So my rule of thumb: reach for WebSockets only when you actually need the client to talk back.

