The first token is a tie — single-user metrics for short poll, long poll, SSE, and WebSocketLook again at the TTFT row. All four land in the same ~300 ms ballpark.
The fastest transport wasn’t actually faster.
That was the first result that caught me off guard.
In this benchmark, your time-to-first-token is set mostly by how long the model takes to produce token one, far more than by the transport carrying it. Every token in my demo costs 300 ms to make, and the transport adds only a few dozen milliseconds on top (a little more for short polling, which has to find the token on a later knock), so the first one shows up in the low 300s of milliseconds whether you’re short-polling or holding a WebSocket open. Here, transport is a rounding error next to generation time. The first token lands when the model has written it, not a moment sooner because you reached for a fancier pipe.
